===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*(s)mer-|id=remember}}
From {{inh|en|enm|remembren}}, from {{der|en|fro|remembrer||to remember}}, from {{der|en|LL.|rememorari||to remember again}}, from {{m|la|re-}} + {{m|la|memor||mindful}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*mer-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*(s)mer-||to think about, be mindful, remember}}. Cognate with {{cog|ang|mimorian}}, {{m|ang|mymerian||to remember, commemorate}}, {{cog|ang|mÄmorian||to deliberate, plan out, design}}. More at {{l|en|mammer}}.

{{rel-top|etymology note}}
The success of the [[Old French]] word was helped by its proximity in sound and meaning to an existing Germanic word: {{cog|ang|mimorian}}, {{m|ang|mymerian||to remember, commemorate}} from {{cog|gem-pro|*mimrÅnÄ…}}, {{m|gem-pro|*mÄ«mrÅnÄ…||to remember, be mindful}}, from the same Indo-European source, and is akin to {{cog|stq|mÄ«merje||to ponder, reflect}}, {{cog|gml|mimeren||to ponder, meditate}}, {{cog|dum|mimeren||to reflect, think to oneself}} ({{cog|nl|mijmeren||to muse, reflect deeply}}), {{cog|ang|mimor||mindful}}, {{cog|non|MÃ­mir}}, {{m|non|Mim||Norse god of memory}}, {{cog|ang|mÄmrian||to think out, design}}. Related to {{l|en|mourn}}.

Displaced native {{cog|enm|ÈemuneÈen||to remember|sc=Latinx}}, from {{cog|ang|Ä¡emynegian||to remember, remind}}; {{cog|enm|minnen||to remember, have in mind}}, from {{cog|non|minna||to remind}}; {{cog|enm|munden}}, {{m|enm|Èemunden||to bear in mind, remember|sc=Latinx}}, from {{cog|ang|Ä¡emynd||memory, remembrance}}; {{cog|enm|ithenchen}}, {{m|enm|Èethenchen||to think on, remember|sc=Latinx}}, from {{cog|ang|Ä¡eÃ¾encan}}; {{cog|enm|manien||to remind, mention, remember}}, from {{cog|ang|manian||to admonish, remind, mention}}.
